## Reasoning
To migrate the `ProductService.java` file to Quarkus, we need to address the issue with the `@Stateless` annotation. In Java EE, `@Stateless` is used to define a stateless session bean, but in Quarkus, we can use CDI (Context and Dependency Injection) beans instead.

The suggested replacement for `@Stateless` is to use a scope annotation such as `@ApplicationScoped`. This annotation defines the scope of the bean, which in this case is the application scope.

Here are the steps to update the file:

1. Remove the `@Stateless` annotation from the `ProductService` class.
2. Add the `@ApplicationScoped` annotation to the `ProductService` class.
3. Ensure that the `@ApplicationScoped` annotation is imported from the correct package.

The `@ApplicationScoped` annotation is part of the CDI specification, so we need to make sure that the CDI dependency is included in the `pom.xml` file.

## Updated File
```java
package com.redhat.coolstore.service;

import com.redhat.coolstore.model.CatalogItemEntity;
import com.redhat.coolstore.model.Product;
import com.redhat.coolstore.utils.Transformers;

import jakarta.enterprise.context.ApplicationScoped;
import jakarta.inject.Inject;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.stream.Collectors;

import static com.redhat.coolstore.utils.Transformers.toProduct;

@ApplicationScoped
public class ProductService {

    @Inject
    CatalogService cm;

    public ProductService() {
    }

    public List<Product> getProducts() {
        return cm.getCatalogItems().stream().map(entity -> toProduct(entity)).collect(Collectors.toList());
    }

    public Product getProductByItemId(String itemId) {
        CatalogItemEntity entity = cm.getCatalogItemById(itemId);
        if (entity == null)
            return null;

        // Return the entity
        return Transformers.toProduct(entity);
    }

}
```

## Additional Information
To complete this migration, the following dependency needs to be added to the `pom.xml` file:
```xml
<dependency>
    <groupId>jakarta.enterprise</groupId>
    <artifactId>jakarta.enterprise.cdi-api</artifactId>
</dependency>
```
However, since we are migrating to Quarkus, we should use the Quarkus CDI extension instead:
```xml
<dependency>
    <groupId>io.quarkus</groupId>
    <artifactId>quarkus-arc</artifactId>
</dependency>
```
This will provide the necessary CDI functionality for the Quarkus application.
